Step by Step Reasoning:
1. Key psychological mechanisms:
   • A responder’s evaluation of an offer appears to depend on comparing the actual monetary offer (split_self) to an internally computed fairness reference.
   • The fairness reference is based on the participant’s relative contribution (token_self vs. token_opp) to a shared earning. When the offer falls below this reference, the responder experiences a penalty.
   • The degree of dissatisfaction or “inequity aversion” may grow more than linearly with the deviation from fairness; therefore, a quadratic penalty mechanism is introduced.

2. How these mechanisms interact:
   • First, compute a fairness reference (fair_share) as a proportional split of the combined earnings based on the participant’s token contribution relative to the total tokens.
   • Compare the actual offer (split_self) to the fairness reference. If the offer meets or exceeds the reference, the utility remains equal to the monetary amount offered. If the offer is below the reference, a penalty is subtracted which grows as the square of the deviation, scaled by a learnable inequity penalty parameter.

3. Mathematical form to capture interactions:
   • The model uses a piecewise function: when split_self ≥ fair_share the utility equals split_self; when split_self < fair_share it equals split_self minus a quadratic penalty term α · (fair_share − split_self)².

4. Parameters needed:
   • A single learnable parameter, alpha, representing the strength of the quadratic penalty for offers falling below the fairness reference. Its bounds can be set generously, for example between 0 and 10.

5. Mapping to observable behavior:
   • The model directly uses variables available from the dataset: token_self, token_opp, combined_earning, and split_self.
   • The computed fair_share serves as the benchmark against which each offer is evaluated.
   • The resulting utility, U_accept, is lower (and potentially negative) when the deviation (fair_share − split_self) is large, indicating an unlikely acceptance based on psychological sensitivity to inequity.

